1
00:04:01,112 --> 00:04:03,580
It is better to settle
these matters in the courts...

2
00:04:03,782 --> 00:04:05,215
... than on the streets.

3
00:04:05,417 --> 00:04:08,352
And new laws are needed
at every level.

4
00:04:08,553 --> 00:04:11,920
But law alone cannot make
men see right.

5
00:04:12,490 --> 00:04:15,618
We are confronted primarily
with a moral issue.

6
00:04:15,827 --> 00:04:17,818
The heart of the question is...

7
00:04:18,029 --> 00:04:21,396
... whether all Americans are
to be afforded equal rights...

8
00:04:21,599 --> 00:04:23,362
...and equal opportunities...

9
00:04:24,202 --> 00:04:26,602
... whether we treat
our fellow Americans...

10
00:04:26,805 --> 00:04:28,136
...as we want to be treated.

11
00:04:28,339 --> 00:04:31,331
If an American,
because his skin is dark...

12
00:04:31,810 --> 00:04:35,337
...cannot eat lunch
in a restaurant open to the public...

13
00:04:35,547 --> 00:04:37,515
...if he cannot send his children...

14
00:04:37,715 --> 00:04:39,910
... to the best public school
available...

15
00:04:40,251 --> 00:04:43,982
...if he cannot vote
for the officials who represent him...

16
00:04:44,589 --> 00:04:47,558
...if, in short, he cannot enjoy
the full and free life...

17
00:04:47,759 --> 00:04:49,693
... which all of us want...

18
00:04:50,628 --> 00:04:52,960
... then who among us
would be content...

19
00:04:53,231 --> 00:04:55,392
... to have the color
of his skin changed?

20
00:04:56,234 --> 00:04:58,395
Who among us would then be content...

21
00:04:58,603 --> 00:05:01,800
... with the counsels
of patience and delay?

22
00:05:02,407 --> 00:05:04,932
One hundred years
of delay have passed...

23
00:05:05,143 --> 00:05:07,737
...since President Lincoln
freed the slaves...

24
00:05:08,213 --> 00:05:12,616
... yet their heirs, their grandsons
are not fully free.

25
00:05:12,984 --> 00:05:15,817
They are not yet freed
from the bonds of injustice.

26
00:05:16,154 --> 00:05:19,487
They are not yet freed
from social and economic oppression.

27
00:05:19,691 --> 00:05:21,591
That looks like a police car.

28
00:05:22,026 --> 00:05:25,826
And this nation, for all
its hopes and all its boasts...

29
00:05:26,030 --> 00:05:29,693
... will not be fully free
until all its citizens are free.

30
00:05:30,869 --> 00:05:33,963
We preach freedom
around the world and we mean it.

31
00:05:34,172 --> 00:05:36,504
And we cherish our freedom
here at home.

32
00:05:36,708 --> 00:05:38,300
Are we to say to the world...

33
00:05:38,510 --> 00:05:41,035
...and much more importantly,
to each other...

34
00:05:41,246 --> 00:05:44,682
... that this is a land of the free,
except for the Negroes?

35
00:05:45,083 --> 00:05:48,484
That we have no second-class citizens,
except Negroes?

36
00:05:48,786 --> 00:05:51,254
That we have no class
or caste system...

37
00:05:51,456 --> 00:05:55,722
...no ghettos, no master race,
except with respect to Negroes?

38
00:05:56,361 --> 00:06:00,388
Now the time has come for
this nation to fulfill its promise.

39
00:06:00,832 --> 00:06:02,800
The events in Birmingham
and elsewhere...

40
00:06:03,368 --> 00:06:07,202
...have so increased the cries
for equality that no city...

41
00:06:07,572 --> 00:06:11,303
...or state or legislative body
can prudently choose...

42
00:06:11,509 --> 00:06:12,771
... to ignore them.

43
00:06:12,977 --> 00:06:14,911
The fires of frustration
and discord...

44
00:06:15,113 --> 00:06:18,571
...are burning in every city,
North and South...

45
00:06:18,883 --> 00:06:21,374
... where legal remedies
are not at hand.

46
00:06:21,586 --> 00:06:23,918
Redress is sought in the streets.

47
00:06:24,589 --> 00:06:27,422
We face a moral crisis
as a country and a people.

48
00:06:28,326 --> 00:06:31,386
It cannot be met
by repressive police action.

49
00:06:31,729 --> 00:06:34,755
It is a time to act
in the Congress...

50
00:06:34,999 --> 00:06:38,059
...in your state
and local legislative body...

51
00:06:38,269 --> 00:06:41,761
...and above all,
in all of our daily lives.

52
00:06:41,973 --> 00:06:44,134
A great change is at hand...

53
00:06:44,375 --> 00:06:45,706
...and our task...

54
00:06:45,910 --> 00:06:49,175
...our obligation is to make
that revolution, that change...

55
00:06:49,747 --> 00:06:52,045
...peaceful and constructive for all.

56
00:06:52,250 --> 00:06:53,649
Those who do nothing...

57
00:06:53,985 --> 00:06:56,954
...are inviting shame
as well as violence.

58
00:06:57,555 --> 00:07:00,149
Those who act boldly
are recognizing right...

59
00:07:01,426 --> 00:07:02,893
...as well as reality.

60
00:07:04,228 --> 00:07:05,058
Medgar!

61
00:07:05,263 --> 00:07:06,992
-Get down!
-Get the baby!

62
00:07:11,336 --> 00:07:12,564
Medgar!

63
00:07:22,113 --> 00:07:23,808
Oh, my God!

64
00:07:27,151 --> 00:07:29,483
Daddy! Daddy!

65
00:07:29,687 --> 00:07:31,211
Daddy, I love you!

66
00:07:34,425 --> 00:07:36,188
Daddy, don't die!

67
00:07:37,495 --> 00:07:39,326
I want my daddy!

68
00:07:44,369 --> 00:07:46,064
Turn me loose.

69
00:07:46,804 --> 00:07:48,396
Turn me loose.

70
00:07:55,446 --> 00:07:59,473
Medgar Evers believed in this country.

71
00:08:00,284 --> 00:08:04,311
It now remains to be seen
whether his country believed in him.

72
00:08:21,873 --> 00:08:24,603
The Citizens Council's raised
thousands for your defense.

73
00:08:24,809 --> 00:08:26,936
Money's pouring in
from all over the South.

74
00:08:27,145 --> 00:08:29,613
Nice likeness.
What do you think, boys?

75
00:08:29,814 --> 00:08:31,577
Mr. Beckwith, glad to see you.

76
00:08:31,783 --> 00:08:33,774
Mighty glad to be here.

77
00:08:34,452 --> 00:08:36,920
And isn't it true
your husband was the first...

78
00:08:37,121 --> 00:08:40,022
...to attempt to integrate
the University of Mississippi?

79
00:08:41,659 --> 00:08:44,287
At the time of his death,
he was involved in a lawsuit...

80
00:08:44,495 --> 00:08:47,362
...to integrate the public
school system, wasn't he?

81
00:08:49,000 --> 00:08:52,265
Your husband must've had quite
a few enemies, would you agree?

82
00:08:52,470 --> 00:08:53,767
Yes, he did.

83
00:08:53,971 --> 00:08:57,202
Your eldest boy,
his name is Kenyatta, isn't it?

84
00:08:57,475 --> 00:08:59,739
Darrell Kenyatta Evers.

85
00:09:00,111 --> 00:09:02,079
Kenyatta's a Mau Mau name, isn't it?

86
00:09:02,280 --> 00:09:03,269
Objection.

87
00:09:03,481 --> 00:09:04,675
Sustained.

88
00:09:04,882 --> 00:09:09,046
Isn't it true that over 100 people
were arrested during a demonstration...

89
00:09:09,253 --> 00:09:11,448
...that your husband
organized boycotting...

90
00:09:11,956 --> 00:09:15,551
...a department store in downtown
Jackson known as Kennington's?

91
00:09:15,827 --> 00:09:17,158
Who's that?

92
00:09:17,829 --> 00:09:19,057
Ross Barnett.

93
00:09:19,263 --> 00:09:20,730
You're kidding.

94
00:09:21,332 --> 00:09:24,358
Nope. You don't see that
every day of the week.

95
00:09:24,569 --> 00:09:28,505
A former governor shaking hands
with an assassin in front of the jury.

96
00:09:28,706 --> 00:09:31,869
There's not a court in America
that would stand for that.

97
00:09:32,076 --> 00:09:34,203
What's America got to do
with anything?

98
00:09:34,412 --> 00:09:36,073
This is Mississippi.

99
00:09:36,547 --> 00:09:38,515
Byron De La Beckwith.

100
00:09:38,916 --> 00:09:41,578
-You live in Greenwood, Mississippi?
-Y es, sir.

101
00:09:41,786 --> 00:09:43,720
My mother was a Yerger.

102
00:09:43,921 --> 00:09:45,786
Her mother was Susan Yerger...

103
00:09:45,990 --> 00:09:48,982
...a close personal friend
of Mrs. Jefferson Davis.

104
00:09:49,193 --> 00:09:50,888
You shoot Medgar Evers?

105
00:09:51,095 --> 00:09:52,255
No, sir!

106
00:09:53,297 --> 00:09:55,197
Your Honor, may l?

107
00:09:56,000 --> 00:09:58,366
Mr. Beckwith, is this your rifle?

108
00:09:59,137 --> 00:10:00,035
Let's see.

109
00:10:02,540 --> 00:10:05,771
Well, it bears a similarity...

110
00:10:05,977 --> 00:10:08,070
...but I couldn't say for certain.

111
00:10:08,312 --> 00:10:11,042
I don't record the
serial numbers of my weapons...

112
00:10:11,249 --> 00:10:15,879
...and my gun was stolen
from my home several days before...

113
00:10:16,154 --> 00:10:17,678
...this whole business.

114
00:10:48,319 --> 00:10:50,014
How do you feel, Delay?

115
00:10:50,254 --> 00:10:52,745
I got tears in my eyes.

116
00:10:52,990 --> 00:10:54,287
For Dixie, huh?

117
00:11:14,812 --> 00:11:15,938
In summation...

118
00:11:16,147 --> 00:11:19,514
...not only did surveillance cameras
provide us with a visual record...

119
00:11:19,851 --> 00:11:21,580
...of the crime being committed...

120
00:11:21,786 --> 00:11:26,189
...but four eyewitnesses observed
the defendant removing his mask...

121
00:11:26,390 --> 00:11:28,881
...upon exiting the convenience store.

122
00:11:29,360 --> 00:11:32,989
Short of you ladies and gentlemen
attending the actual event...

123
00:11:33,197 --> 00:11:36,462
...we don't feel the state
could have a stronger case.

124
00:11:36,701 --> 00:11:37,531
Thank you.

125
00:11:38,569 --> 00:11:39,695
Counsel?

126
00:11:41,439 --> 00:11:43,373
Hey, Bobby. How'd it go?

127
00:11:43,674 --> 00:11:46,336
Through a combination
of superior lawyering...

128
00:11:46,544 --> 00:11:50,708
...and a less than stellar performance
by our criminal, I got a conviction.

129
00:11:50,915 --> 00:11:52,007
Congratulations.

130
00:11:52,250 --> 00:11:56,482
My rape victim's reluctant to testify.
Can you handle the Harrison motion?

131
00:11:56,687 --> 00:11:58,279
-You bet.
-You're a lifesaver.

132
00:11:58,489 --> 00:12:01,458
-DeLaughter, your wife just called.
-What'd she want?

133
00:12:01,659 --> 00:12:05,993
To remind you you're having lunch with
her mother and your parents at 1:00.

134
00:12:06,197 --> 00:12:07,994
How could I forget?

135
00:12:08,232 --> 00:12:09,324
Bobby.

136
00:12:11,702 --> 00:12:14,136
-You seen this?
-Yes, I have.

137
00:12:14,338 --> 00:12:17,796
Evers' widow is calling for
the re-prosecution of De La Beckwith.

138
00:12:18,009 --> 00:12:20,443
Ed, this guy was killed
over 25 years ago.

139
00:12:20,945 --> 00:12:24,676
Dig up whatever you can on Medgar Evers
and be in my office at 3:00.

140
00:12:24,882 --> 00:12:26,372
Ed, this is ridiculous.

141
00:12:26,584 --> 00:12:27,642
Well, sure it is.

142
00:12:27,852 --> 00:12:29,149
But if we try to bury this...

143
00:12:29,353 --> 00:12:32,447
...she'll have every black politician
climbing all over me.

144
00:12:33,324 --> 00:12:35,451
My office, 3:00.

145
00:12:45,469 --> 00:12:47,903
Do we have any files here
on Medgar Evers?

146
00:12:48,105 --> 00:12:48,935
Who?

147
00:12:49,140 --> 00:12:52,871
The civil rights leader
that got himself shot in the 1960s?

148
00:12:53,077 --> 00:12:57,343
I just saw that file. It was next
to the one on the Lindbergh baby.

149
00:12:57,715 --> 00:13:00,149
Clara, just bring me what we have.

150
00:13:10,795 --> 00:13:12,126
Good afternoon, sir.

151
00:13:23,140 --> 00:13:25,404
Did you make Hinds County safer today?

152
00:13:25,609 --> 00:13:29,739
You know how it is with criminals.
It's like finding a gray hair.

153
00:13:29,981 --> 00:13:32,643
You pull one and two more pop up
to take its place.

154
00:13:33,417 --> 00:13:36,113
I love those earrings.
Have you worn them before?

155
00:13:36,320 --> 00:13:40,450
I've had them for quite some time.
I just never wear them during the day.

156
00:13:40,658 --> 00:13:43,855
You see that nonsense
about the Sovereignty Commission?

157
00:13:44,061 --> 00:13:45,756
Yeah, isn't that awful?

158
00:13:46,230 --> 00:13:49,529
That fool, Rea Hederman.
Since he took over that paper...

159
00:13:49,734 --> 00:13:53,101
...Iiberals like Jerry Mitchell
been trying to rewrite history.

160
00:13:53,537 --> 00:13:57,997
The Sovereignty Commission was a fine
organization that did a lot of good.

161
00:13:58,275 --> 00:14:00,505
Dixie, would you pass me the butter?

162
00:14:00,778 --> 00:14:04,179
Why do they dig up things
that happened 25 years ago anyway?

163
00:14:04,382 --> 00:14:07,180
Medgar Evers' widow
wants to reopen the case.

164
00:14:07,685 --> 00:14:09,516
You can't be serious.

165
00:14:09,854 --> 00:14:11,788
Ed asked me to look into it.

166
00:14:15,459 --> 00:14:17,586
You just tell him, "No, thank you."

167
00:14:17,795 --> 00:14:22,164
When will these people get it through
their heads that the '60s are over?

168
00:14:22,366 --> 00:14:25,802
The 1860s and the 1960s.

169
00:14:26,037 --> 00:14:29,029
I thought they found
that Beckwith fella not guilty.

170
00:14:29,240 --> 00:14:32,073
Actually, there were two hung juries.

171
00:14:33,310 --> 00:14:36,711
The reason I know is because
my late husband, Judge Moore...

172
00:14:36,914 --> 00:14:39,246
...was a spectator
at both those trials.

173
00:14:39,583 --> 00:14:41,949
He'd never miss a day.
And he told me...

174
00:14:42,219 --> 00:14:46,815
...that they'd never convict Beckwith,
no matter how many trials they had.

175
00:14:47,158 --> 00:14:50,525
It's just political. I don't
think anything will come of it.

176
00:14:50,728 --> 00:14:53,128
Son, for your sake,
it had better not.

177
00:14:53,330 --> 00:14:55,195
You want to be a judge someday.

178
00:14:55,399 --> 00:14:59,267
You persecute a 70-year-old man,
guilty or not, over some nigger...

179
00:14:59,470 --> 00:15:02,928
...you'll have everybody in Mississippi
lined up against you.

180
00:15:03,140 --> 00:15:04,732
-Hey, Howard.
-How you doing?

181
00:15:04,942 --> 00:15:07,570
Y'all got any
of that crawdad chowder today?

182
00:15:07,778 --> 00:15:08,972
Yes, sir.

183
00:15:09,180 --> 00:15:12,013
-How many for crawdad chowder?
-Oh, come on!

184
00:15:13,751 --> 00:15:17,448
Mrs. Evers, Mr. Dees, I'm Jerry Mitchell
from The Clarion-Ledger.

185
00:15:17,655 --> 00:15:20,647
I broke the story on the jury
tampering in your husband's case.

186
00:15:21,992 --> 00:15:23,391
-I talked to you on the phone.
-That's right.

187
00:15:23,594 --> 00:15:27,792
Thank you for your good work. I can't
tell you how much it's appreciated.

188
00:15:27,998 --> 00:15:29,761
I'm just doing my job, ma'am.

189
00:15:29,967 --> 00:15:33,960
What do you think your chances are
of getting the D.A. to reopen the case?

190
00:15:34,171 --> 00:15:36,162
I've passed this way before.

191
00:15:36,373 --> 00:15:40,366
Let's just say I've adopted
an attitude of tempered optimism.

192
00:15:43,848 --> 00:15:45,475
DeLaughter, hear the news?

193
00:15:45,683 --> 00:15:47,844
President Lincoln just got shot.

194
00:15:48,052 --> 00:15:50,316
Some guy named Booth did it.

195
00:15:51,822 --> 00:15:55,781
The Sovereignty Commission, a state
agency, worked against the D.A...

196
00:15:55,993 --> 00:15:59,986
...to ensure the jury had Beckwith
sympathizers to keep him out of jail.

197
00:16:00,197 --> 00:16:02,358
That's grounds for a new trial.

198
00:16:02,566 --> 00:16:03,658
With all due respect...

199
00:16:03,868 --> 00:16:07,201
...those old files have been
leaking out for years.

200
00:16:07,404 --> 00:16:11,636
They only ran background checks which,
while unethical, was not illegal.

201
00:16:11,842 --> 00:16:16,074
We can't prove jury tampering.
I'd like you to meet Bob DeLaughter.

202
00:16:16,547 --> 00:16:17,377
How do you do?

203
00:16:17,748 --> 00:16:19,648
-Pleasure.
-Mr. Morris Dees...

204
00:16:19,850 --> 00:16:21,374
...the Southern Poverty Law Center.

205
00:16:21,619 --> 00:16:23,314
-How you doing?
-I was explaining...

206
00:16:23,521 --> 00:16:25,318
...that in order for us
to pursue this...

207
00:16:25,523 --> 00:16:27,991
...we'll need more
than an article in a newspaper.

208
00:16:28,192 --> 00:16:29,557
We'll need new evidence.

209
00:16:29,760 --> 00:16:31,660
In 1964, you had
a mountain of evidence.

210
00:16:31,862 --> 00:16:33,659
All you gotta do is retry Beckwith.

211
00:16:33,864 --> 00:16:36,389
On the basis of that alone,
you'll get a conviction.

212
00:16:37,668 --> 00:16:40,899
As you can see, the mountain
has crumbled a bit.

213
00:16:42,039 --> 00:16:43,028
What's this?

214
00:16:43,240 --> 00:16:46,937
That's all that's left of the
state's case against De La Beckwith.

215
00:16:47,144 --> 00:16:50,079
Just a few pages
of the old police report.

216
00:16:50,281 --> 00:16:53,079
-Where's the gun? Where--
-Where's the bullet?

217
00:16:53,350 --> 00:16:57,184
Where's the original trial transcript?
Where are the files? Beats me.

218
00:16:58,822 --> 00:17:00,619
Are you telling us it is lost?

219
00:17:00,824 --> 00:17:02,689
I'm telling you, we don't have it.

220
00:17:02,993 --> 00:17:04,221
Well, that's outrageous.

221
00:17:05,062 --> 00:17:07,963
Even if we had the evidence,
we'd never get around...

222
00:17:08,165 --> 00:17:11,362
...to the Sixth Amendment right
to a speedy trial.

223
00:17:11,569 --> 00:17:15,562
Mr. Dees would agree that 25 years
isn't exactly what you'd call speedy.

224
00:17:16,640 --> 00:17:18,267
May I see that?

225
00:17:18,475 --> 00:17:20,568
Mrs. Evers, this is
pretty strong stuff.

226
00:17:21,412 --> 00:17:22,640
I'd like to see it.

227
00:17:32,590 --> 00:17:35,081
"June 13, 1963.

228
00:17:35,392 --> 00:17:37,724
To the Jackson Police Department:

229
00:17:38,062 --> 00:17:41,930
When you catch whoever killed
the nigger, pin a medal on him...

230
00:17:42,333 --> 00:17:46,167
...because he just did Mississippi
one hell of a favor.

231
00:17:47,271 --> 00:17:49,933
June 14, 1963.

232
00:17:50,140 --> 00:17:52,973
A female who refused
to identify herself stated...

233
00:17:53,177 --> 00:17:56,408
...that she'd heard a rumor
that Medgar Evers' wife...

234
00:17:56,647 --> 00:18:00,583
...had gotten jealous of Lena Horne,
who appeared with Evers at a rally...

235
00:18:00,784 --> 00:18:04,345
...and might have gotten
her brother-in-law to kill Evers."

236
00:18:07,024 --> 00:18:10,755
Who wouldn't be jealous of Lena Horne?
What a beautiful woman.

237
00:18:11,795 --> 00:18:13,023
Y es, ma'am.

238
00:18:13,230 --> 00:18:17,826
The cops wrote that garbage down
because they actually took it seriously.

239
00:18:18,035 --> 00:18:18,967
Mr. Dees.

240
00:18:19,536 --> 00:18:23,700
Do you think the police in Washington,
D.C. would have written it up...

241
00:18:23,907 --> 00:18:27,638
...if some nitwit said Jackie Kennedy
had a hand in J.F.K.'s death...

242
00:18:27,845 --> 00:18:30,643
...because her husband ran around
with Marilyn Monroe?

243
00:18:30,881 --> 00:18:32,007
What's your point?

244
00:18:32,216 --> 00:18:35,276
The murder of Medgar Evers
was a race crime...

245
00:18:35,486 --> 00:18:37,511
...a political crime.
An assassination.

246
00:18:37,888 --> 00:18:39,856
Beckwith is free today...

247
00:18:40,057 --> 00:18:42,582
...thanks to a racist jury,
a racist police department...

248
00:18:42,793 --> 00:18:44,954
...and a racist D.A.'s office.

249
00:18:45,162 --> 00:18:47,630
Twenty-five years ago,
Waller and this office...

250
00:18:47,831 --> 00:18:49,958
...went after Beckwith
not once but twice.

251
00:18:50,167 --> 00:18:52,226
I don't need to sit here and listen--

252
00:18:52,936 --> 00:18:56,201
Twenty-five years ago,
I sat on the witness stand...

253
00:18:56,407 --> 00:18:59,638
...and I watched as the former
governor of this state...

254
00:18:59,843 --> 00:19:03,006
...shook hands with the man
who murdered my husband...

255
00:19:03,814 --> 00:19:05,509
...while I was on the stand.

256
00:19:08,585 --> 00:19:10,485
I don't expect you to understand...

257
00:19:10,688 --> 00:19:13,122
...the pain and suffering
my family went through...

258
00:19:13,324 --> 00:19:14,985
...but I did come here thinking...

259
00:19:15,192 --> 00:19:18,889
...that this office might want
to see justice finally served.

260
00:19:21,999 --> 00:19:25,435
You've given me all the reasons
why you can't pursue this.

261
00:19:25,636 --> 00:19:28,764
Perhaps you can find
one reason why you can.

262
00:19:29,406 --> 00:19:31,203
Good afternoon, gentlemen.

263
00:19:51,128 --> 00:19:52,618
Ed Peters is a good man...

264
00:19:52,830 --> 00:19:55,424
...but as you can see,
we simply don't have a case.

265
00:19:55,632 --> 00:19:59,466
I know you've been living
with this thing for a long while...

266
00:20:00,471 --> 00:20:02,632
...but maybe it's just time you....

267
00:20:03,707 --> 00:20:04,969
Let it go?

268
00:20:05,542 --> 00:20:08,409
I can understand why you'd
think that, Mr. DeLaughter.

269
00:20:08,612 --> 00:20:10,978
For years, I said
the same thing to Medgar.

270
00:20:11,181 --> 00:20:13,911
"Let it go.
Let's get out of Mississippi."

271
00:20:14,418 --> 00:20:16,215
Do you know what he said to me?

272
00:20:16,820 --> 00:20:19,311
" I don't know if I'm going
to heaven or to hell...

273
00:20:19,523 --> 00:20:21,650
...but I'm going from Jackson."

274
00:20:22,259 --> 00:20:24,056
Good afternoon, Mr. DeLaughter.

275
00:20:56,827 --> 00:20:58,692
Hey, everybody, I'm home.

276
00:21:07,104 --> 00:21:08,298
Hey, tiger.

277
00:21:08,972 --> 00:21:10,200
Hi, Dad.

278
00:21:11,141 --> 00:21:15,043
You sure you got enough distractions?
I can go get your Game Boy.

279
00:21:15,646 --> 00:21:16,772
Dad.

280
00:21:16,980 --> 00:21:18,208
Hi, Daddy.

281
00:21:18,649 --> 00:21:19,581
Hi, Dad.

282
00:21:19,783 --> 00:21:23,844
-Did you bring me a lollipop?
-I did. I got one for Claire too.

283
00:21:24,054 --> 00:21:27,023
-Thanks, Daddy.
-How was school today, sweetie?

284
00:21:27,224 --> 00:21:29,522
Did Miss Collins like
the bracelet you made?

285
00:21:29,827 --> 00:21:31,556
Daddy, tell us a story.

286
00:21:32,262 --> 00:21:35,129
-A real scary one.
-Claire, you want to hear a story?

287
00:21:35,332 --> 00:21:37,300
Okay, but not too scary.

288
00:21:37,501 --> 00:21:41,198
Let's go to Mommy and Daddy's room,
because we don't wanna disturb Burt.

289
00:21:44,575 --> 00:21:48,102
-You want something to eat?
-No, I got something at the office.

290
00:21:49,947 --> 00:21:51,676
Thanks for letting me know.

291
00:22:34,458 --> 00:22:36,016
Honey, what are you doing up?

292
00:22:36,226 --> 00:22:37,693
I can't sleep.

293
00:22:37,895 --> 00:22:39,556
The ghost is back.

294
00:22:39,963 --> 00:22:42,056
I'll go. I'll go.

295
00:22:43,200 --> 00:22:46,101
The ghost is back?
Where is he this time?

296
00:22:46,303 --> 00:22:47,270
In my bed.

297
00:22:47,471 --> 00:22:50,565
Really? We'll just have
to see about that.

298
00:22:53,977 --> 00:22:56,810
You were right.
He's right there on the bed.

299
00:22:57,514 --> 00:22:58,606
No, Daddy.

300
00:22:58,815 --> 00:23:00,976
Now he's over by the window.

301
00:23:03,387 --> 00:23:04,649
I see.

302
00:23:06,290 --> 00:23:08,588
Your bottle tree was
supposed to keep him away.

303
00:23:08,926 --> 00:23:11,588
Maybe I don't have
the right kind of bottles.

304
00:23:11,929 --> 00:23:13,328
You know, baby...

305
00:23:14,398 --> 00:23:16,832
...when we lived in Natchez,
there was a ghost...

306
00:23:17,034 --> 00:23:18,626
...that lived right next door...

307
00:23:18,835 --> 00:23:21,963
...in the remains of this house
that got burned during the war.

308
00:23:22,439 --> 00:23:26,307
And sometimes he'd come over
and get right in my closet.

309
00:23:26,610 --> 00:23:27,804
How'd you make him go away?

310
00:23:28,178 --> 00:23:30,578
Granny would come in
and sing a song...

311
00:23:30,781 --> 00:23:32,806
...and before you knew it,
he was gone.

312
00:23:33,550 --> 00:23:35,108
What'd she sing?

313
00:23:35,552 --> 00:23:38,419
She sang the song every ghost
from Mississippi loves.

314
00:23:38,922 --> 00:23:40,014
Sing it, Daddy.

315
00:23:40,524 --> 00:23:41,684
All right.

316
00:23:43,060 --> 00:23:46,188
I wish I was in the land of cotton

317
00:23:46,396 --> 00:23:48,626
Old times there are not forgotten

318
00:23:48,832 --> 00:23:50,129
Look away

319
00:23:50,434 --> 00:23:51,765
Look away

320
00:23:52,035 --> 00:23:55,334
Look away, Dixieland

321
00:23:55,539 --> 00:23:57,871
In Dixieland where I was born

322
00:23:58,208 --> 00:24:00,836
Early on one frosty morn'

323
00:24:01,178 --> 00:24:03,806
Look away, look away

324
00:24:04,014 --> 00:24:07,142
Look away, Dixieland

325
00:24:07,718 --> 00:24:09,948
Oh, I wish I was in Dixie

326
00:24:10,153 --> 00:24:12,917
Hooray, hooray

327
00:24:13,123 --> 00:24:15,819
In Dixieland I'll take my stand

328
00:24:16,026 --> 00:24:18,995
To live and die in Dixie

329
00:24:19,196 --> 00:24:21,289
Away, away

330
00:24:21,565 --> 00:24:24,159
Away down South

331
00:24:24,601 --> 00:24:26,432
In Dixie

332
00:24:30,440 --> 00:24:32,772
I'd ask what's new,
but I'm afraid you'd tell me.

333
00:24:32,976 --> 00:24:35,536
My readers are on the edge
of their collective seat.

334
00:24:36,913 --> 00:24:38,380
Will Mr. DeLaughter go after
Byron De La Beckwith?

335
00:24:38,582 --> 00:24:42,985
The D.A.'s office will investigate
the possibility of reopening the case.

336
00:24:43,186 --> 00:24:46,553
I didn't go to law school,
but that sounds like bullshit.

337
00:24:46,757 --> 00:24:47,815
Nice talking to you.

338
00:24:48,025 --> 00:24:49,515
Have a nice day.

339
00:25:11,081 --> 00:25:14,517
Can you tell me how I can get
ahold of Lewis Skinner...

340
00:25:14,718 --> 00:25:15,810
...or Fred Sanders?

341
00:25:16,019 --> 00:25:20,251
If you want Lewis Skinner, you'll need
a shovel and six hours of digging time.

342
00:25:20,657 --> 00:25:21,783
What's Fred's status?

343
00:25:21,992 --> 00:25:24,722
As far as I know,
he's still aboveground.

344
00:25:26,363 --> 00:25:28,888
Back in '63,
none of those houses were there.

345
00:25:29,099 --> 00:25:31,090
That was all vacant lot.

346
00:25:31,301 --> 00:25:34,236
And this here was
all covered over with brush.

347
00:25:34,471 --> 00:25:37,531
I got out here eight minutes
after the call came in.

348
00:25:37,741 --> 00:25:41,973
The way Mrs. Evers yelled at me,
you'd think I was the one who done it.

349
00:25:43,180 --> 00:25:47,412
This is where they found the gun,
hidden in some honeysuckle vines.

350
00:25:47,884 --> 00:25:49,943
Any idea where
that gun might be today?

351
00:25:50,153 --> 00:25:51,211
Hell, no.

352
00:25:51,421 --> 00:25:52,513
Back in those days...

353
00:25:52,723 --> 00:25:56,318
...evidence had a habit
of disappearing after the trials.

354
00:25:56,793 --> 00:25:57,919
Look at that.

355
00:25:58,128 --> 00:26:01,256
My grandmother could have
picked Evers off from over here.

356
00:26:01,465 --> 00:26:03,365
That's where he was shot.

357
00:26:03,567 --> 00:26:06,092
That big tree wasn't there
at the time.

358
00:26:06,436 --> 00:26:07,960
There was blood everywhere.

359
00:26:08,171 --> 00:26:11,072
All over the driveway,
all over the car.

360
00:26:11,274 --> 00:26:13,640
It was as if somebody
had butchered a hog.

361
00:26:13,877 --> 00:26:18,610
But Evers must've been one hell of a
strong man because somehow he managed...

362
00:26:18,815 --> 00:26:21,147
...to drag himself
all the way up to his door.

363
00:26:21,485 --> 00:26:25,478
After that bullet tore through his back,
it slammed through that window...

364
00:26:25,689 --> 00:26:27,156
...crashed through a wall...

365
00:26:27,357 --> 00:26:31,225
...ricocheted off the refrigerator
and busted the coffeepot.

366
00:26:31,428 --> 00:26:35,524
We found it on the kitchen counter
next to a watermelon.

367
00:26:36,867 --> 00:26:37,959
You're kidding me.

368
00:26:38,368 --> 00:26:39,596
No, sir.

369
00:26:44,574 --> 00:26:45,939
Did he have any kids?

370
00:26:46,143 --> 00:26:50,477
If my memory serves, I believe there
were three little ones there that night.

371
00:26:54,885 --> 00:26:59,447
What kind of man shoots another man
in the back in front of his family?

372
00:27:00,624 --> 00:27:03,149
I love the land of my birth.

373
00:27:03,927 --> 00:27:06,521
I do not mean
just America as a country...

374
00:27:06,763 --> 00:27:08,287
...but Mississippi...

375
00:27:08,498 --> 00:27:10,159
... the state in which I was born.

376
00:27:11,268 --> 00:27:14,294
So the deplorable things
I speak of here today...

377
00:27:14,538 --> 00:27:16,836
... will be said to you
in hopes of a future...

378
00:27:17,607 --> 00:27:20,838
... where such will not
be the case in Mississippi.

379
00:27:21,044 --> 00:27:22,807
In the horrific deaths...

380
00:27:23,013 --> 00:27:24,503
...of Emmett Till...

381
00:27:24,881 --> 00:27:27,076
...Reverend G. W. Lee...

382
00:27:27,450 --> 00:27:30,180
...Lamar Smith and a variety
of other atrocities...

383
00:27:30,387 --> 00:27:32,821
...no one has been convicted.

384
00:27:33,423 --> 00:27:38,190
And we feel those guilty of having
committed these ungodly acts...

385
00:27:38,395 --> 00:27:41,956
...had the feeling of assurance
that nothing ever would be done.

386
00:27:42,265 --> 00:27:44,529
For you see, ladies and gentlemen...

387
00:27:45,168 --> 00:27:49,400
... white juries have yet to convict
a white man in Mississippi...

388
00:27:49,673 --> 00:27:52,198
...guilty of a crime against a Negro.

389
00:27:52,976 --> 00:27:57,572
The failure of the so-called decent
or moderate white person...

390
00:27:57,781 --> 00:28:01,217
... to take a positive
and uncompromising stand....

391
00:28:01,418 --> 00:28:02,680
Who's that?

392
00:28:04,254 --> 00:28:05,619
Medgar Evers.

393
00:28:08,725 --> 00:28:10,352
Why are you looking at it?

394
00:28:12,495 --> 00:28:15,953
I just wanted to get
an idea of who he was.

395
00:28:17,000 --> 00:28:19,366
I'd like to get
an idea of who you are.

396
00:28:20,003 --> 00:28:21,732
What's that supposed to mean?

397
00:28:22,472 --> 00:28:24,940
I was willing to go down
that road with you...

398
00:28:25,141 --> 00:28:28,201
...when you got out of law school
and did that pro bono work.

399
00:28:28,411 --> 00:28:31,938
And when you worked for
that Jew lawyer who ran you ragged.

400
00:28:32,415 --> 00:28:36,215
I minded a little when you turned down
that offer from Morse & Braggs...

401
00:28:36,419 --> 00:28:39,286
...so you could be assistant D.A.
at one-fourth the salary.

402
00:28:39,489 --> 00:28:42,856
But I'll be damned if I spent
10 years supporting your career...

403
00:28:43,059 --> 00:28:44,458
...just so you can humiliate me.

404
00:28:45,061 --> 00:28:47,325
You're gonna pursue this, aren't you?

405
00:28:48,331 --> 00:28:51,391
You're gonna humiliate me
in front of my friends...

406
00:28:51,601 --> 00:28:53,694
...my family and the entire state.

407
00:28:53,904 --> 00:28:55,929
I'm just looking
at a couple of tapes.

408
00:28:56,539 --> 00:28:59,064
Fine. Look at your tapes.

409
00:28:59,376 --> 00:29:01,105
That's all you'd better do.

410
00:29:06,716 --> 00:29:08,274
-Why not?
-Because you can't win.

411
00:29:08,485 --> 00:29:09,315
Who says?

412
00:29:09,586 --> 00:29:12,419
-The Sixth Amendment.
-Suppose I could get around it.

413
00:29:12,622 --> 00:29:15,887
It's one thing for
the grieving widow to carry on--

414
00:29:16,293 --> 00:29:20,195
Suppose an argument could be made
that the Sixth Amendment doesn't apply.

415
00:29:20,397 --> 00:29:21,921
You want to retry Beckwith?

416
00:29:22,165 --> 00:29:23,097
Fine.

417
00:29:23,366 --> 00:29:28,167
Dig up 26-year-old physical evidence
which probably no longer exists...

418
00:29:28,605 --> 00:29:32,735
...identify it, and then you'll have
to locate the key witnesses...

419
00:29:32,943 --> 00:29:35,707
...who, if you find them,
are probably dead or senile.

420
00:29:35,912 --> 00:29:38,380
Their testimony could be read
from the transcript.

421
00:29:38,581 --> 00:29:42,278
We haven't seen a certified
transcript in over 25 years.

422
00:29:42,485 --> 00:29:45,010
-What if I found one?
-Let's say, by some miracle...

423
00:29:45,221 --> 00:29:48,782
...you found one, got an indictment.
Then by some greater miracle...

424
00:29:48,992 --> 00:29:53,156
...the state Supreme Court and U.S.
Supreme Court didn't throw it out...

425
00:29:53,363 --> 00:29:56,025
...and you actually got to trial.
What if you lose?

426
00:29:56,232 --> 00:30:00,168
The whole state, which is supposed
to have changed so much...

427
00:30:00,370 --> 00:30:03,066
...will be facing the worst
public relations disaster...

428
00:30:03,273 --> 00:30:06,538
...since that black kid, Emmett Till,
bobbed up out of the river.

429
00:30:12,182 --> 00:30:14,412
Are you telling me
I can't go after this?

430
00:30:14,617 --> 00:30:16,847
I'm telling you
you're dealing with the past.

431
00:30:17,053 --> 00:30:19,487
Mississippi's not
a place you wanna be.

432
00:30:24,194 --> 00:30:27,322
Hopefully, Jerry Mitchell can
keep this thing alive for us.

433
00:30:27,564 --> 00:30:30,761
Jerry Mitchell's fine, but
what we need is national press.

434
00:30:30,967 --> 00:30:35,529
Darrell, CNN won't run a major story
about how the D.A. of Hinds County...

435
00:30:35,739 --> 00:30:38,708
...is refusing to re-prosecute a case...

436
00:30:38,908 --> 00:30:40,899
...that's a quarter of a century old.

437
00:30:41,111 --> 00:30:43,671
Stop annoying your grandmama.

438
00:30:43,880 --> 00:30:48,078
The greatest joy in your mother's life
is being annoyed by her grandchildren.

439
00:30:48,284 --> 00:30:50,718
Next to being annoyed by you, Walter.

440
00:30:51,454 --> 00:30:52,421
I'll get it.

441
00:30:52,622 --> 00:30:54,681
I'm not here no matter who it is.

442
00:31:00,964 --> 00:31:01,988
Who?

443
00:31:03,900 --> 00:31:05,663
Just a minute, please.

444
00:31:06,503 --> 00:31:08,198
I want you to eat those beans.

445
00:31:08,405 --> 00:31:10,100
It's long distance from Jackson.

446
00:31:10,340 --> 00:31:13,241
A man by the name of DeLaughter.
You want me to take it?

447
00:31:13,443 --> 00:31:15,308
No, I'll take it.

448
00:31:15,612 --> 00:31:17,273
Eat those beans.

449
00:31:18,048 --> 00:31:19,948
I don't eat beans.

450
00:31:25,221 --> 00:31:26,381
Hello, Mrs. Evers.

451
00:31:26,589 --> 00:31:29,820
I know you probably left here
feeling pretty discouraged...

452
00:31:30,026 --> 00:31:33,393
...but I hope you understand
Mr. Peters was just being realistic.

453
00:31:33,596 --> 00:31:35,257
I understand perfectly.

454
00:31:35,465 --> 00:31:36,830
I also wanted you to know...

455
00:31:37,033 --> 00:31:39,866
...that we are going to
be keeping this case open.

456
00:31:42,806 --> 00:31:43,932
Mrs. Evers?

457
00:31:44,140 --> 00:31:47,303
Did it suddenly occur to
Mr. Peters that he'd better...

458
00:31:47,510 --> 00:31:51,446
...start making nice with the
black community before November?

459
00:31:52,015 --> 00:31:54,176
-Mrs. Evers--
-He made it clear to me...

460
00:31:54,417 --> 00:31:57,614
...that in addition to having
no evidence and no witnesses...

461
00:31:57,821 --> 00:31:59,482
...he also had no interest.

462
00:31:59,722 --> 00:32:03,954
Looking into this wasn't so much
Mr. Peter's idea as it was mine.

463
00:32:04,160 --> 00:32:06,321
-Yours?
-Yes, ma'am.

464
00:32:08,898 --> 00:32:12,493
Judge Russel Moore was perhaps
the most racist judge...

465
00:32:12,702 --> 00:32:14,966
...in the history
of the state of Mississippi.

466
00:32:15,171 --> 00:32:18,106
Why would his son-in-law
be interested in this case?

467
00:32:18,374 --> 00:32:22,140
Mrs. Evers, I'm 37 years old,
just like Medgar was...

468
00:32:22,345 --> 00:32:24,677
...and I've got three kids,
like he did.

469
00:32:25,081 --> 00:32:27,675
I was 11 years old
when your husband was killed...

470
00:32:27,884 --> 00:32:30,011
...and I hardly remember him at all.

471
00:32:31,020 --> 00:32:35,184
But I went by your house the other day
and I could see him there...

472
00:32:36,025 --> 00:32:37,856
...watering his lawn...

473
00:32:38,428 --> 00:32:40,191
... working on his roof...

474
00:32:40,997 --> 00:32:42,931
...playing with his children.

475
00:32:43,600 --> 00:32:47,593
No man has the right to take
another man away from his children.

476
00:32:49,372 --> 00:32:52,034
I appreciate the call,
Mr. DeLaughter.

477
00:32:52,709 --> 00:32:54,609
I'll keep in touch, Mrs. Evers.

478
00:33:00,216 --> 00:33:01,911
Did you plan on telling me...

479
00:33:02,452 --> 00:33:05,114
...or was I just gonna read
about it in the papers?

480
00:33:07,223 --> 00:33:10,056
We should be at the
Walkers' house in 15 minutes.

481
00:33:11,561 --> 00:33:14,291
Well, I've got a lot
of work to do here.

482
00:33:18,401 --> 00:33:19,766
Suit yourself.

483
00:33:24,874 --> 00:33:27,775
Nobody gives a goddamn
what Byron De La Beckwith did...

484
00:33:27,977 --> 00:33:30,241
...to some Medgar Evers 26 years ago.

485
00:33:30,446 --> 00:33:34,314
Hell, Larry Smith got shot down
in his own driveway just last week.

486
00:33:34,617 --> 00:33:36,380
And it wasn't for no civil rights.

